## Test Anti-Pattern Audit: `ProductCatalogTests.cs`

This test suite is a textbook example of **"coverage theater"** — every production method is called (achieving line coverage) but almost nothing is actually verified. Here's the severity-ranked list:

---

### 🔴 Critical — Tests That Verify Nothing

**1. `AddProduct_Works` (line 17)** — Fire-and-forget; no assertion at all.
```csharp
// FIX: verify state was persisted
_catalog.AddProduct(product);
var stored = _catalog.GetProduct("SKU-001");
Assert.AreEqual("Widget", stored!.Name);
Assert.AreEqual(9.99m, stored.Price);
```

**2. `UpdatePrice_Works` (line 32)** — Calls `UpdatePrice` but never checks the new price.
```csharp
// FIX: assert post-condition
_catalog.UpdatePrice("SKU-001", 14.99m);
Assert.AreEqual(14.99m, _catalog.GetProduct("SKU-001")!.Price);
```

**3. `RemoveProduct_Works` (line 38)** — Never verifies the product is gone.
```csharp
// FIX: assert deletion
_catalog.RemoveProduct("SKU-001");
Assert.IsNull(_catalog.GetProduct("SKU-001"));
```

**4. `ApplyBulkDiscount_Works` (line 68)** — Applies 10% discount, never checks prices changed.
```csharp
// FIX: verify each product's price reduced
_catalog.ApplyBulkDiscount(0.10m);
Assert.AreEqual(8.991m, _catalog.GetProduct("SKU-001")!.Price);
Assert.AreEqual(17.991m, _catalog.GetProduct("SKU-002")!.Price);
```

**5. `GetProductCount_Works` (line 63)** — Doesn't even assert the count; also tests on an *empty* catalog.
```csharp
// FIX: add products then assert count
_catalog.AddProduct(new Product("SKU-001", "Widget", 9.99m));
Assert.AreEqual(1, _catalog.GetProductCount());
```

**6. `ImportFromCsv_Works` (line 84)** — Imports but never checks the product exists in the store.
```csharp
// FIX: verify round-trip
_catalog.ImportFromCsv("SKU-001,Widget,9.99");
var p = _catalog.GetProduct("SKU-001");
Assert.AreEqual("Widget", p!.Name);
Assert.AreEqual(9.99m, p.Price);
```

---

### 🟠 High — Weak Assertions (`IsNotNull` on collections/strings)

**7. `GetProduct_Works` (line 23)** — Only asserts `IsNotNull`; doesn't check field values. A bug returning `new Product("","",0)` would pass.
```csharp
// FIX: assert field values
Assert.AreEqual("SKU-001", result!.Sku);
